1. Tool Name: vibecheck

2. Manual Setup or Licenses:
   - GPU: a CUDA-capable NVIDIA GPU is expected (the per-benchmark configs assume
     it). vibecheck falls back to CPU if CUDA is absent, but slower.
   - Gurobi: the default `graph` mode uses Gurobi (gurobipy). The pip wheel's
     size-limited license suffices for the regular-track benchmarks; a full
     Gurobi license is only needed for very large models.

3. Use CPU/GPU AWS Instance? GPU

4. Scripts (all take a leading "v1" version string):
   - install_tool.sh v1
   - prepare_instance.sh v1 <category> <onnx> <vnnlib>
       zombie cleanup, GPU check, pre-parse .pkl cache, warmup.
   - run_instance.sh v1 <category> <onnx> <vnnlib> <results_file> <timeout>
       writes verdict (unsat/sat/unknown/timeout) on line 1; for `sat`, the
       counterexample s-expression follows.

   Each script brackets its stdout with banner lines that VNNCOMP captures and
   that the local parser keys off:
       [vibecheck:<script>] BEGIN <key=val ...>
       [vibecheck:<script>] END   verdict=... elapsed=...s ...
   vibecheck runs --verbose by DEFAULT (per-phase progress, line-buffered so a
   timed-out/SIGKILL'd run still flushes its trace instead of leaving an empty
   log). The verdict in the run END banner comes from <results_file> and is
   authoritative.

   Env overrides: VNNCOMP_PYTHON_PATH (dir of the python to use; default the
   repo .venv), VIBECHECK_PKL_CACHE_DIR (pre-parse cache location; default
   /tmp/vibecheck_pkl), VIBECHECK_GPU_RESET=1 (GPU power-mode reset in prepare;
   needs passwordless sudo, off by default), VIBECHECK_QUIET=1 (drop --verbose),
   VIBECHECK_HEARTBEAT=N (emit a per-phase "[heartbeat]" line every N seconds so
   a STALLED phase is visible in the captured log — the way to localize a hang
   before the timeout kill; --verbose alone only prints at phase boundaries).

5. Local helpers (NOT used by the competition harness):
   - run_benchmarks.py <category|all|regular> [--bench-version 1.0]
       Replays prepare+run over a benchmark's instances.csv into a results.csv.
       Handles the VNNCOMP 2026 versioned layout (benchmarks/<cat>/<version>/);
       --bench-version selects 1.0 (v1 specs; default) or 2.0 (v2; not yet
       parseable). --log-dir DIR saves each instance's stdout for inspection.
   - parse_log.py LOG|DIR  (or pipe a log on stdin)
       Summarizes captured run logs: verdict, timing, net/spec shape, and — for
       a run that was killed/timed out — the last heartbeat phase it hung in.
